Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

Your code has **three** thread-termination patterns:

| Location | Pattern | Problem on .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `RunLoop()` — `while(true)` | Cancellable work loop | No way to stop it without `Abort` |
| `Stop()` — `_thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `SYSLIB0046` (obsolete in .NET 9, unreliable in .NET 8) |
| `Stop()` — `_thread.Abort()` | Fallback forced termination | `PlatformNotSupportedException` — **crashes at runtime** |

## Pre-existing Bug

The original code has a **lost-signal race**: if `Enqueue` is called twice before `RunLoop` wakes, `_newEvent.Set()` is called twice but `Reset()` clears the signal — the second item stays stuck in the queue until the next enqueue.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            // GetConsumingEnumerable blocks until an item is available
            // and throws OperationCanceledException when the token is cancelled.
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Normal shutdown — exit the loop.
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _queue.Add(item);
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();   // No more items accepted
        _cts.Cancel();            // Wakes the thread if blocked in GetConsumingEnumerable
        _thread?.Join(5000);      // Wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | `BlockingCollection<string>` | Thread-safe producer-consumer with built-in blocking; eliminates the manual lock, the signal, and the lost-signal bug |
| `while (true)` | `foreach (GetConsumingEnumerable(token))` | Blocks until an item arrives *or* the token is cancelled — no busy loop, no manual `WaitOne`/`Reset` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative cancellation wakes `GetConsumingEnumerable` by signalling the token's wait handle |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Not available on .NET 8. The `Cancel()` + `Join(5000)` is sufficient because the loop checks the token cooperatively |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` *(implicit)* | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | The new exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` and `BlockingCollection` must be disposed to avoid timer/handle leaks |

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — This isn't a warning; it **throws at runtime**. Removing it is mandatory.

2. **`Thread.Interrupt` is also obsolete** — `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9 and unreliable even on .NET 8. Don't swap `Abort` for `Interrupt`.

3. **Cancellation is cooperative** — If `Handle(item)` does long-running work, it won't be interrupted mid-execution. Pass the token into `Handle` and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints if responsiveness matters.

4. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — Leaking it causes timer and callback leaks. Always wrap ownership in `IDisposable`.

5. **`CompleteAdding()` before `Cancel()`** — Call `CompleteAdding()` first so any concurrent `Add()` gets a clean `InvalidOperationException` rather than silently losing items.
